{
  "text": ", respectively) [CITATION_1] . We could only find measurements of PP concentrations in major Arctic rivers for the Yukon [CITATION_2] , and for a smaller Arctic river [CITATION_3] . We combine Arctic river sediment yield data from [CITATION_4] with discharge-weighted total PP data from [CITATION_5] (571 \u03bcg g \u00c01 ), and mean labile PP phase data from the Amazon and Mississippi Rivers, where by far the most extensive PP fractionation records are available for riverine environments (~40% of total PP; Table 3 ) [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , to derive estimates of Arctic river basin yields for comparison. We acknowledge that these estimates are crude, because they are based on values reported from temperate/tropical rivers and use a different Fe-P extraction to this study. Despite this, yields are similar to GrIS glacial catchments (Table 4) . We estimate labile P yields of 1.4-21.3 kg km \u00c02 yr \u00c01 for the Arctic rivers, which are <37% of LG yields and similar to KS estimates.",
